Meet Ron Chez, the man behind the gift







Sun, 10/04/2015 - 7:00am | Tracy Crane







Image Gallery:

Center for Wounded Veterans Dedication» more
Photo by: Robin Scholz
Dedication ceremony for the Center for Wounded Veterans in Higher Education on UI campus in Urbana on Friday, October 2, 2015.










 

URBANA — Ron Chez knows a wise investment when he sees one.
A successful financial management consultant with his own corporation, the University of Illinois graduate has advised a who's who of the Fortune 500 — from JP Morgan Chase and Motorola to Apple and Amazon.
But one of his latest investments is in people.
"It's an obligation. I feel like it's an obligation," Chez said of his $6 million donation that covered nearly half the cost of building the Center for Wounded Veterans in Higher Education at his alma mater. "I always said, 'If I was blessed with the opportunity, if I could, I would do things to benefit others.' I didn't come from a wealthy family at all, at all.
"There's nothing more important than providing services to the people who defend the country and put themselves at great risk."
A Chicago-area native, Chez enrolled at the UI in the late '60s as a physical education major on a baseball scholarship.
"I played for a bit, and I became a has-been," said Chez, who switched his major to political science, and in 1969, graduated Phi Beta Kappa in what he describes as "a giant upset."
On a visit back to campus years later, Chez remembers looking for his name on the Bronze Tablets, the list of graduates who earned University Honors, and discovering his was the only one out of order — not in a column, separate from the others.
"The only one, and it looks like I snuck in there and put my name up there," he said, laughing. "I thought it was extraordinarily humorous."
After the UI, Chez enrolled, on scholarship, to Northwestern University's law school.
"I went for three days, and that was sufficient," said Chez, who, signed up for the Army shortly thereafter.
"It was at a time when hardly anybody was shooting anybody, so that was a blessing," he said.
After the military, he started his own business in 1979, focusing on consulting and venture capital, generally involving the stock market and private deals.
Today, he's the president and sole owner of Ronald L. Chez Inc., a financial management consulting corporation. He is also the chairman of the board of Epiworks, a compound semiconductor materials company in Champaign.
But he has a fun side, too.
He's the executive producer of Woody Allen's recent movies, like "Magic in the Moonlight" and another that's being shot this year and stars Steve Carell, among other Hollywood notables.
"We are friends, yes," Chez said of Allen. "But I don't do anything really but pay for the movie with another person. He doesn't give scripts out."
Chez said it's not his best use of money and admits he wouldn't invest in anyone else's movies.
"It's just my regard for his special genius, so I did it because it's so wildly different from other stuff I do," he said. "It's fun to do it, and there is a reasonable probability that I would not lose money."
On the philanthropic side, he's a member of the Wounded Warriors board and formed the Chez Family Foundation. The latter funds the Chez Scholars program, which pays the full college freight of academically gifted but economically disadvantaged Chicago Public Schools graduates.
In its eighth year at the UI, the program has funded about 40 students.
"It's a stunning record of performance by these young people," Chez said.
The idea behind the wounded veteran center donation came after Chez read an article about the UI's Beckwith Hall, a residence center for students with disabilities, and asked for a tour on visit to campus.
Tanya Gallagher, the dean of the UI College of Applied Health Sciences, was his tour guide. She mentioned plans for her big idea — to build a one-of-a-kind one-stop-shop for disabled veterans attending school here.
"Almost immediately, he said, 'I want to help with that,'" Gallagher said.
Chez's $6 million pledge was the lead gift in the fundraising project, "which was instrumental in moving the project forward," Gallagher said. "Actually, essential."
"She pursued it vigorously," Chez said. "Loads of people have ideas, but she had a concept and made it happen. It's the people who come up with the idea and then doggedly pursue it. So they're the ones who deserve great credit here."
 



 






 

