  Probation for man who threatened prosecutor, child
Thu, 07/27/2017 - 8:50am | Mary Schenk










URBANA — A Bellflower man who prosecutors say threatened to harm himself, his child and a prosecutor while getting court-ordered counseling has been resentenced to two more years of probation.
Judge Brett Olmstead on Wednesday told Gregory Todd, 40, that all the decisions he had made in his aggravated battery case were born out of his anger.
 















  First Busey's second-quarter net income up 33% over 2016
Thu, 07/27/2017 - 7:00am | Ben Zigterman


CHAMPAIGN — In its second quarter, First Busey Corp. reported a 33 percent increase in net income compared with a year ago.
Net income increased from $12.4 million a year ago to $16.5 million in the second quarter. Compared with last quarter, when net income was $15.2 million, net income increased 8.6 percent.
 















  Urbana mayor sets sights on new city administrator
Thu, 07/27/2017 - 7:00am | Natalie Wickman


URBANA — Now that she's got a budget in place, Mayor Diane Marlin is turning her focus to hiring a city administrator, an official Urbana has been without for 10 years.
 















  C-U at Home mentor's new title: Crime Fighter of Year
Thu, 07/27/2017 - 7:00am | Marcus Jackson










SAVOY — Growing up in Rantoul, Tony Comtois had the police called on him a few times. In recent years, the police have been calling the 52-year-old to tap into his expertise and experience in dealing with the homeless population in Champaign County.
 















  Trump-related tumult triggering surge of Democratic candidates
Thu, 07/27/2017 - 7:00am | Tom Kacich










CHARLESTON — A third Democrat has filed to run in next year's Democratic primary in the 15th Congressional District, which makes three more than the number of Democrats who wanted to take on longtime Congressman John Shimkus in 2016.
 















  Illinois Lottery says state budget impasse cost it almost $4M in sales
Thu, 07/27/2017 - 7:00am | Ben Zigterman










CHAMPAIGN — For about a week, Illinois retailers weren't able to sell Powerball and Mega Millions lottery tickets, because of the state budget impasse.
Ty Brown, a cashier at Discount Smoke Shop in Champaign, said he noticed a drop in sales for those tickets.
"I would say so," he said. "And there was an increase in instant tickets."
 















  Urbana police making video on how to act during a traffic stop
Thu, 07/27/2017 - 7:00am | Natalie Wickman


URBANA — The police department will create an informational video for the public about preferred and undesirable ways to act during a traffic stop.
Preston James, the city's community-relations specialist, is writing the video's script and said it will include different scenarios of how traffic stops can go.
 















  Coke Zero getting new name, recipe
Thu, 07/27/2017 - 7:00am | The Associated Press










NEW YORK (AP) — Coke Zero is getting revamped as Coke Zero Sugar.
The new name is intended to make clearer that the drink has no sugar, and a new recipe is intended to make the drink taste more like regular Coke. The company isn't specifying what it's changing aside from saying it tweaked the "blend of flavors." It says the drink will use the same artificial sweeteners.
 















  Jim Dey: S.B. 1: Who's not the boss of whom?
Thu, 07/27/2017 - 7:00am | Jim Dey


Send me S.B. 1, says the governor of Illinois.
Make me, replies Democratic Senate President John Cullerton.
 















  Marcus Jackson/About Town: 'I don't think I could ever retire'
Thu, 07/27/2017 - 7:00am | Marcus Jackson










CHAMPAIGN — At 70 years old, Rob Gorham is still working, chasing his 17-month-old golden retriever, Maverick, around the house, with no plans to retire anytime soon.
"I don't think I could ever retire," he said. "If you can get involved in a quest that's noble, why would you quit? What if you miss an opportunity to reach people?"
 











